		</a><br>

				<span class=text_smallest>
								</span>

								
			
			
									<p>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
										Viewed 120 times<br>
									</span>

									<img src='/i/skins/default/icon_rating_5.gif' border=0 alt='1 rating - 5.0 average' width=55 height=10>
									</td>

						<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#0C142B" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
			<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; " >
												<DIV></DIV>
<DIV><FONT size=3>The new changes to Bard AoE songs are really a bad change for the Bard class in general, but not for most of the reasons I have seen noted on boards, at least in my opinion.&nbsp; The area kiting of bards has been taken to ridiculous extremes and requires remedy, but consider the following:</FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT size=3></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>1.&nbsp; The first song bards get that damages opponents is Chords of Dissonance, at level 2.&nbsp; Bards now will have to stand still and melee, effectively, for this song to take effect at all.&nbsp; Also, since the song is an area effect song, young bards will be unable to use this song&nbsp;effectively except against a single opponent, which now begs the question:&nbsp; why is it an area effect song at all?</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>2.&nbsp; The next song Bards get to damage opponents is Brusco's Boastful Bellow at level 12, which does&nbsp;8 damage to a single target within about 25 range units distance.&nbsp; The damage on this song increases very slowly to about 20 damage at level 40.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>3.&nbsp; After the level 12 song, bards get another damage song at level 18, Denon's Disruptive Discord.&nbsp; It is an AoE song.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>4.&nbsp; Next is the level 30 song Denon's Disruptive Discord, a targeted&nbsp;DoT song.&nbsp; The damage for this song is incredibly poor compared to other DoT spells of its level, but it finally frees the bard from relying exclusively on AoE songs for damage potential with any instrument.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>What do these things mean?&nbsp; They mean that the real sufferers in the new patch are not the bards above level thirty who abuse area kiting to the extreme.&nbsp; The real losers will be bards below level 30, who have no means of dealing out musical damage except the abysmally nerfed and ineffective bellow song.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>They also mean that there is now absolutely no reason to attempt to play an instrumental bard before level 30.&nbsp; The lute has been rendered useless except for healing.&nbsp; The trumpet is completely useless now, don't bother even buying one until after level&nbsp;35 when you can use it to mana tap other players on a PvP server, if that's your cup of tea.&nbsp; The drum remains useful for running and DoT&nbsp;after level 30.&nbsp; The flute remains a mysterious and worthless item, except for going invisible.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Finally, what does this do to bards who like to play in groups?&nbsp; Nothing much really, although the AoE songs are now really only useful to&nbsp;a bard in a group that might be meleeing more than one mob at once.&nbsp; Will a bard use an AoE song in a group?&nbsp; No, only against a single target, since using an AoE damage song will break any mesmerizations and get the bard killed by aggroing all the mobs in the fight onto the bard.&nbsp; So why are these songs AoE at all?&nbsp; They have no purpose in solo fighting, and they have no purpose in group fighting either.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>It seems to me that these AoE songs should be turned into single-target songs, since that is now the only use they will have anyway.&nbsp; That way at least the songs will be used by bards in some situations, because as they are right now, young bards will have absolutely no use for them.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>So the new changes will affect the young bards the most, and who are the young bards?&nbsp; They are one of two kinds of players.&nbsp; The first is a twinkie, a secondary character for a higher level character.&nbsp; Twinkies have powerful equipment and ready access to guild groups, and they do not need to rely on songs to level their bards.&nbsp; The second is&nbsp; a new player to Everquest, who builds a bard up from nothing.&nbsp; They will have a very difficult time doing this, as bards will now be very difficult for a new player&nbsp;to level, except in groups, prior to level 30.&nbsp; How many groups will want a young bard too, prior to level 32 with Chorus of Clarity?</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>To me the new change is therefore a bad one for Everquest, for it does not hurt the bards who abused the AoE songs, and it really hurts the ones who actually need them.&nbsp; It will continue to turn new players away from Everquest, or at least away from the bard class, and this is unfortunate, for it is one of the things that makes Everquest particularly appealing and interesting, in my opinion.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Hydrangas, instrumental bard of several different servers.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
																		
										</td></tr>
